Poisoning, schoolchildren, teachers - Cambodia 20010502.0848
[1
Date: 3 May 2001
From: Joe Hughart <jxh8@cdc.gov> [edited

Rapid onset of symptoms such as these suggest chemical poisoning. Heavy
metals and pesticides have caused similar symptoms in past incidents.
Cambodia experienced an incident of mercury dumping and subsequent
poisoning a couple of years ago in another coastal seaport town. The source
of the mercury was an industrial facility in Taiwan. Improper application
and disposal of pesticides have also resulted in contamination of public
water supplies in other developing nations.
The Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry (ATSDR), U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services, will contact the U.S. Agency for
International Development, Office of Foreign Disaster Assistance, to obtain
additional information and to determine whether U.S. technical assistance
may be needed. We will keep ProMED-mail informed of our findings.
­­
Joseph L. Hughart, MPH, RHSP
Deputy Director, Office of Federal Programs
Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry
